  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../library/chinafaqs-fast-track-curbing-emissions">ChinaFAQs: Fast Track to Curbing Emissions?</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/ChinaFAQs_Fast_Track_to_Curbing_Emissions_v1.png" alt="" title="" width="93" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"><div class="filefield-file"><img class="filefield-icon field-icon-application-pdf"  alt="application/pdf icon" src="../sites/all/modules/filefield/icons/application-pdf.png" /><a href="../files/chinainfo/ChinaFAQs_Fast_Track_to_Curbing_Emissions.pdf" type="application/pdf; length=234835">ChinaFAQs_Fast_Track_to_Curbing_Emissions.pdf</a></div></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p><b>Key Points</b></p>

<ul>
<li>China is investing heavily in building 10,000 miles of high-speed passenger rail over the next decade that will carry trains traveling at up to 217 miles per hour.</li>
<li>The system, which will connect most of China‚Äôs major cities, could produce significant gains in energy efficiency if travelers shift to the new trains from aircraft and autos.</li>
<li>High-speed rail could also help unclog China‚Äôs rail freight lines, leading to more energy-efficient cargo transport, according to a recent analysis.</li>
</ul></div>
  </div>
