  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../library/chinafaqs-fuel-economy-standards-china">ChinaFAQs: Fuel Economy Standards In China</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/ChinaFAQs_Fuel_Economy_Standards_in_China-1.png" alt="" title="" width="93" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"><div class="filefield-file"><img class="filefield-icon field-icon-application-pdf"  alt="application/pdf icon" src="../sites/all/modules/filefield/icons/application-pdf.png" /><a href="../files/chinainfo/ChinaFAQs_Fuel_Economy_Standards_in_China.pdf" type="application/pdf; length=331268">ChinaFAQs_Fuel_Economy_Standards_in_China.pdf</a></div></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p><b>Key Points:</b></p>

<ul>
<li>In 2004, China adopted its first nation-wide fuel economy standards for passenger vehicles. They are considered to be the world‚Äôs third toughest, behind Japan‚Äôs and Europe‚Äôs.</li>
<li>The standards ‚Äì which called for average auto efficiency to improve by 15% by 2010 over 2003 levels &#8211; have produced significant gains, even though Chinese cars have become heavier, more powerful, and are more often equipped with automatic transmissions and pollution-control devices that can reduce efficiency.</li>
<li>China has since expanded the standards to cover light-duty trucks, and is eyeing further measures to improve the fuel economy of its motor vehicles.</li>
</ul></div>
  </div>
  </div>
  <div class="views-row views-row-39 views-row-odd">
      
